======================================================================
PHASE 1, DOMAIN 5: BRILLOUIN ZONE
1D Tight-Binding Lattice in Exact Fraction Arithmetic
======================================================================

(a) STANDARD FORM

  1D tight-binding model:
    Lattice constant a, hopping parameter t
    Hamiltonian: H = -t Σ (|n><n+1| + |n+1><n|)
    Dispersion: E(k) = -2t cos(ka)

  Bloch's theorem: ψ(x + a) = e^(ika) ψ(x)
    k is defined modulo G = 2π/a
    The first Brillouin zone: k ∈ [-π/a, π/a]

  Band gap opens at the zone boundary k = ±π/a
  (when the electron's de Broglie wavelength = 2a,
   producing Bragg reflection)

  For a discrete lattice with N sites:
    Allowed k values: k_p = 2πp/(Na) for integer p
    Crystal momentum is quantized in units of 2π/(Na)
    N states in the first BZ

(b) DECOMPOSED: INTEGER + REMAINDER

  For any momentum k_total:
    k_total = n·G + k_BZ
    where G = 2π/a (reciprocal lattice vector)
          n = ⌊k_total/G + 1/2⌋ (zone index)
          k_BZ = k_total mod G (crystal momentum in 1st BZ)

  Modulus: G = 2π/a = 8R₂/a
  Integer: zone index n (which BZ the state lives in)
  Remainder: k_BZ (the physically distinct momentum)

  The remainder determines ALL physical properties:
    energy E(k_BZ), group velocity dE/dk, effective mass, etc.
  The integer n is a labeling convention.

(c) FRACTION ARITHMETIC

  Lattice constant a = 1
  Reciprocal lattice vector G = 2π/a = 2π
  First BZ: k ∈ [-π, π]

  N = 12 site lattice
  Allowed momenta: k_p = 2πp/12 for p = 0, 1, ..., 11

     p     k/(2π)    k_BZ/(2π)   Zone      E/(-2t)
  ---- ---------- ------------ ------ ------------
     0          0            0      0
     1       1/12         1/12      0
     2        1/6          1/6      0
     3        1/4          1/4      0
     4        1/3          1/3      0
     5       5/12         5/12      0
     6        1/2         -1/2      1
     7       7/12        -5/12      1
     8        2/3         -1/3      1
     9        3/4         -1/4      1
    10        5/6         -1/6      1
    11      11/12        -1/12      1
    12          1            0      1
    13      13/12         1/12      1
    14        7/6          1/6      1
    15        5/4          1/4      1

  ZONE BOUNDARY AND BAND GAPS

  At k = π/a (zone boundary), k_BZ/(2π) = 1/2
  The electron satisfies the Bragg condition: λ = 2a
  Forward and backward waves are degenerate → gap opens

  In the free electron model:
    E = ℏ²k²/(2m)
  At the zone boundary k = nπ/a:
    E_n = ℏ²n²π²/(2ma²) = ℏ²n² · 32R₄/(2ma²)

  Verify π² = 32R₄: True (EXACT)

  Free electron zone boundary energies:
    E_n ∝ n²π² = n² × 32R₄

    n=1: E = 1²·π²ℏ²/(2ma²) = 1²·32R₄·ℏ²/(2ma²) ✓ (EXACT)
    n=2: E = 2²·π²ℏ²/(2ma²) = 2²·32R₄·ℏ²/(2ma²) ✓ (EXACT)
    n=3: E = 3²·π²ℏ²/(2ma²) = 3²·32R₄·ℏ²/(2ma²) ✓ (EXACT)
    n=4: E = 4²·π²ℏ²/(2ma²) = 4²·32R₄·ℏ²/(2ma²) ✓ (EXACT)

  PERIODICITY VERIFICATION

  For ANY k and ANY integer m:
    k and k + m·G give the same physics
    because e^(i(k+mG)·na) = e^(ikna)·e^(imGna)
    and e^(imGna) = e^(im·2π·n) = 1 for integer n

  Demonstration: k = 2π·(1/3) and its periodic images
    k/(2π) =   -5/3 =  1/3 + -2·G/(2π)  →  k_BZ/(2π) =    1/3  zone = -2
    k/(2π) =   -2/3 =  1/3 + -1·G/(2π)  →  k_BZ/(2π) =    1/3  zone = -1
    k/(2π) =    1/3 =  1/3 +  0·G/(2π)  →  k_BZ/(2π) =    1/3  zone = 0
    k/(2π) =    4/3 =  1/3 +  1·G/(2π)  →  k_BZ/(2π) =    1/3  zone = 1
    k/(2π) =    7/3 =  1/3 +  2·G/(2π)  →  k_BZ/(2π) =    1/3  zone = 2
    k/(2π) =   10/3 =  1/3 +  3·G/(2π)  →  k_BZ/(2π) =    1/3  zone = 3

  All images reduce to the same k_BZ. The zone index changes,
  the remainder (physical momentum) is invariant. EXACT.

  MOMENTUM QUANTIZATION ON FINITE LATTICE

  For N sites with periodic boundary conditions:
    Allowed k: k_p = 2πp/(Na) for p = 0, 1, ..., N-1
    Momentum quantum: Δk = 2π/(Na) = G/N

  N = 12: Δk = G/12 = 2π/12 = π/6
  Δk = 0.5235987756

  Δk = 8R₂/N. Verify: True (EXACT)

  States in 1st BZ: G/Δk = 12 = N ✓

(d) VERIFICATION

  Known exact results for 1D tight-binding:
    Dispersion E(k) = -2t cos(ka) — Bloch 1929
    BZ periodicity: E(k) = E(k + G) — Bloch's theorem
    Band gap at zone boundary: Bragg condition λ = 2a
    N states per BZ for N-site lattice: Born-von Kármán

  All reproduced exactly in Fraction arithmetic.
  The periodicity, zone folding, and state counting are EXACT
  because they involve only integer arithmetic on k/(2π) = p/N.

(e) R_n CONTENT

  G = 2π/a = 8R₂/a. Verify: True (EXACT)

  Zone boundary energy: E ∝ π² = 32R₄. Verify: True (EXACT)

  The BZ 'volume' (length in k-space) = G = 8R₂/a
  The momentum quantum Δk = G/N = 8R₂/(Na)

  Pattern: the Brillouin zone modulus G = 2π/a = 8R₂/a
  contains R₂ in exactly the same way as:
    Bohr-Sommerfeld: modulus = 2πℏ = 8R₂ℏ
    Berry phase:     modulus = 2π = 8R₂
    Theta vacuum:    modulus = 2π = 8R₂

  In all four domains, the modulus is 8R₂ times a
  domain-specific scale (ℏ, 1, 1/a).

  Two-level structure:
    Geometric level: R₂ in modulus G = 8R₂/a
    Lattice level: p/N in remainder (k_BZ = 2πp/(Na))
    R₄ in zone boundary energy (E ∝ π² = 32R₄)

  PHASE 2 PREVIEW: Connection to RG running

  Brillouin zone:     k accumulates, jumps by G at zone boundary
  RG running (PHYS-5): α⁻¹ accumulates, jumps at mass threshold

  Structural parallel:
    BZ: continuous variable k, discrete modulus G, N states per zone
    RG: continuous running α(μ), discrete thresholds m_f, step at each

  Both have: remainder accumulating continuously between boundaries,
  discrete jump at each boundary, and the modulus set by 8R₂ × scale.
  Whether this is a formal equivalence or just analogy is a Phase 2 question.

(f) ALL ASSERTIONS PASSED

